<font color="#FF0000">REPLY TO LIN</font><br>
<tt>Wed Oct  8 23:21:54 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Lin,<br><br>
Thank you for your sensitive view about the war. If you truly protested the reasons for the war and not those who fought in the war, you have my respect. Such is the way of democracy.<br><br>
SW, who posted above, also has a very good point. SW's sensitivity to historical parallels is a message about which we must all take heed. The Viet Cong and NVA were ruthless assassins whose devastation of people of their own culture was nothing more than ritual cannibalism. The government of Vietnam today smiles outwardly and pulls out fingernails in the back room. Witness to this is the contemporary persecution of Buddhists, who were among those who were  supporters of the initial conflict. Regardless of some of the perceptions and facts about our involvement, a significant component of our being there in the first place had much to do with this aspect. For this reason, SW's point is well taken. The lack of support at home did much to destabilize those who fought, and most probably influenced the outcome we now face.<br><br>
Another point to consider is that there is a considerable gulf in points of view between many who fought *in* the war and many who fought *around* the war. I fought in the war. I have a line in the sand that is very clear. My father and father-in-law fought in WW2, and they have their own line in the sand that is very clear. The reason is that we were the ones shot at. This experience is indescribable pure terror, until you dissociate enough to survive. Many pulled back together after the war. Many did not. I did not. I have PTSD. In WW2, it was called &quot;shell shock&quot;. Such was our rite of passage. It is, therefore, only natural for us to react to challenges in the manner we do. Understand this, and your concern of the continuing disconnect will become more clear and less distressing. In 40 to 50 years or so, there will be none of us left, and all this will be just a bad blotch on history. It is then I hope the lessons of the Vietnam war will stick. 
<p><code>-- art16@ix.netcom.com  (Arthur Varanelli) </code><p>


